@unnumbered Startup mode (CLI/TUI)

@c @man{14}
@c @ifman @unnumberedsubsec Start
ZDL can be started in different ways:

@table @emph
@item @b{A) To enter links and start new downloads:}

@enumerate
@item
automatically generating the list of download links:

@itemize @minus
@item
open a terminal and enter the directory that will contain the downloaded files

@item
start ZDL by typing the command followed by any options

@item
copy the links of the files to download and paste them in the terminal (wrap up after each link)

@item
type @kbd{M-x} (@kbd{M}, the @emph{Meta} key, is @kbd{<Alt>}, @kbd{<Ctrl>} or @kbd{<Esc>})

@end itemize

@item
Using one or more files prepared with a text editor (wrapping after each link) and reachable from the destination directory (indicate a valid path):
@itemize @minus
@item
open a terminal and enter the directory that will contain the downloaded files (alternatively, you can indicate to @emph{ZDL} the working directory)

@item
type the command @command{zdl} followed by the names of the files containing the list of links: @command{zdl} @emph{path/file ...}
@end itemize

@item
By indicating directly to ZDL the links to be processed (if valid links were to be declared invalid, try @emph{1}):
@command{zdl} @emph{link ...}

@item
From the web browser, through the use of additional components (@emph{Flashgot} for @emph{Firefox}, the script @command{zdl-xterm}, the command @command{zdl} in the Conkeror mini-buffer, ...), to the purpose of capturing and saving the stream of a video or another file of any type.

@item
In "daemon" mode (also from interactive mode)

@item
Using an editor, with the option @option{-e} or other more specific (for example, @option{--emacs-nw})
@end enumerate

Files, working directory and links can be entered in any order. All input links are saved in the file @file{links.txt}, in the destination directory.

@item @b{B) To manage downloads already started in "non-interactive" and "daemon" mode:}
by starting the interactive mode in two ways:

@enumerate
@item
in console from the download destination directory, using the command @command{zdl -i} or @command{zdl --interactive}

@item
in "non-interactive" (standard) mode, by typing the @kbd{i} key
@end enumerate
@end table


@c @end man
