@unnumbered Modi
ZDL can be used in different ways:

@unnumberedsec Standard output mode (default and @emph {lite}: @option{-l, --lite}).
Two different @emph{standard output modes} are available: the default one, which punctually informs the user of each operation performed, communicating the relevant data of the downloads in progress and the @emph{lite} mode, extremely compact in the representation of the downloads and @emph{silent} with respect to extraction and analysis processes. The second mode can be started with the option @option{-l} (@option{--lite}) or configured as @emph{default} through the configuration interface: @command{zdl [-c|--configure]}. It is particularly suitable for the user who uses ZDL as an alternative browser downloader, for example through the @emph{Flashgot} extension.
@*
The @emph{standard output modes} are equipped with a @ref{Readline} and accept the following commands, expressed in key combinations:

@table @kbd
@item M-i
start @emph{interactive mode}. The standard output of the terminal is transferred to another mode, without however suspending the activities of the previous mode, which proceed silently.
@item M-e
start the default editor (@ref{Editor}). As for the previous command, the activities are not suspended while using an editor to manipulate the list of links to be processed.
@item M-c
clears information (temporary files) of completed downloads.
@item M-q
allows the exit from ZDL without interrupting the downloaders, which continue to record useful data for a ZDL restart: downloads can be controlled through the functions of an @emph{interactive mode} but, in the event of interruptions, they must be processed using @emph{standard output} or @emph{daemon} modes or through @emph{GUI} or @emph{WebUI}.
@item M-k
kills all processes started in the directory, without deleting temporary files.
@end table

@unnumberedsec Interactive mode (@option{-i, --interactive}).
Allows manual control of downloads (@ref{Check downloads}) and other operations, described in the same interface. @emph{It does not process links} and it is only a @emph{client}: to start the download it is necessary to run an instance @emph{server} of ZDL, like @emph{standard output} or @emph{deamon} modes. The latter can be started from the same interactive mode.
@*
This mode of use is the one that provides more information on the @emph{state} of downloads. Its screen is automatically updated every 15 seconds or manually by typing any key.

